to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of severe headache. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 170/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her Glasgow Coma Scale score is 15/15. Neurological examination reveals neck stiffness but is otherwise normal. A computed tomography scan of her head shows blood in the subarachnoid space.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arteriovenous malformation","Head trauma","Ruptured berry aneurysm","Hypertension","Amyloid angiopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH), characterised by thunderclap headache and neck stiffness. Understanding the common causes of different types of intracranial haemorrhage is crucial for clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERuptured berry aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of non-traumatic SAH, accounting for approximately 85% of cases. These aneurysms typically occur at arterial bifurcations in the Circle of Willis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriovenous malformations\u003C/strong\u003E can cause SAH but are a much less common cause, accounting for only about 5% of cases. They are more commonly associated with intracerebral haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHead trauma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause SAH but is more commonly associated with epidural and subdural haemorrhages. Traumatic SAH typically has a different distribution pattern on imaging compared to aneurysmal SAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of intracerebral haemorrhage, particularly in the basal ganglia, thalamus, pons, and cerebellum, but is not a primary cause of SAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloid angiopathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes lobar intracerebral haemorrhages in elderly patients and is not a significant cause of SAH.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epidural haemorrhage typically occurs due to trauma causing middle meningeal artery rupture.","Subarachnoid haemorrhage is most commonly caused by ruptured berry aneurysms.","Arteriovenous malformations commonly present with intracerebral haemorrhage."],"references":["Thilak S, Brown P, Whitehouse T, Gautam N, Lawrence E, Ahmed Z, Veenith T. Diagnosis and management of subarachnoid haemorrhage. Nat Commun. 2024 Feb 29;15(1):1850. doi: 10.1038/s41467-024-46015-2. PMID: 38424037; PMCID: PMC10904840.","Meyers S. Subarachnoid Hemorrhage Related to Ruptured Berry Aneurysm. Acad Pathol. 2017 Jul 24;4:2374289517716463. doi: 10.1177/2374289517716463. PMID: 28815205; PMCID: PMC5528913.","Ziu E, Khan Suheb MZ, Mesfin FB. Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. [Updated 2023 Jun 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441958/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T09:14:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T09:14:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9272"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66044"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":